Never force a stretch beyond your comfort level. You should feel a mild tension, but sharp or stabbing pain is a clear signal that you must stop immediately to prevent bodily harm.
Stretching your triceps is often overlooked in gym routines. Reach your hand down the center of your back and gently push your elbow down with your other hand to increase flexibility.
To stretch your lats, grab a stationary object and lean back. This helps create space in the rib cage and relieves the tension that builds up after heavy rows or pull-ups.
The side-lunge stretch is perfect for targeting your adductors. Shift your body weight to one side while keeping the other leg straight, ensuring you feel a gentle pull in your inner thigh.
Deep breathing during stretching helps to lower your heart rate after intense cardio. Use the time to transition from the high-energy environment of the gym to a state of calm recovery.
The standing quad stretch is a staple for lower body days. Hold onto a partner or equipment for support and keep your knees together to maximize the tension on the quads.
Stretching your neck by pulling it gently to the side helps release tension from heavy barbell shrugs. Do not force the movement; let the weight of your hand provide the resistance.
To stretch your lats reach across your body while holding onto a vertical pole. Lean back and away from the pole to feel a deep stretch along the side of your back.
For the lat pulldown, pull the bar toward your upper chest. Do not lean back too far, as that shifts the focus away from your back muscles to your lower back.
Keep your core braced tightly as if someone is about to punch you in the stomach. This protects your spine during overhead presses and prevents your lower back from arching.
When using the cable machine, keep your movements smooth and steady. Avoid jerky motions, as they can cause unnecessary wear and tear on your tendons and ligaments over the time.
Ensure your grip is symmetrical on the barbell during overhead presses. Keep your core tight to avoid excessive lower back arching. This helps to stabilize your body and prevent potential injury.
Always keep your shoulder blades depressed during pull-ups. Avoid shrugging your shoulders toward your ears. This keeps the tension on your lats and protects your neck from feeling any unnecessary strain.
When performing cable rows, keep your chest out and shoulders back. Do not use your momentum to pull the handle. Focus on squeezing your shoulder blades together at the very end.
Check your stance width when doing sumo deadlifts. Your feet should be wider than shoulder-width apart. Keep your chest up to ensure your spine remains safe during the entire heavy lift.
Do not arch your back excessively during seated overhead presses. Keep your feet planted firmly to provide a solid foundation. This protects your spine while you work your shoulder muscles hard.
Always ask if someone is finished with a set before you start taking plates off their barbell. It is polite to wait until they are completely done with their exercise.
