Tipping customs vary dramatically worldwide, from being almost mandatory in North America to being considered offensive in Japan. A final review of these practices helps travelers avoid embarrassing social gaffes.
Before finalizing our cross-cultural handbook, we must review how different nations describe heavy rain, comparing the English "cats and dogs" to the Portuguese "showering pocketknives" idiom.
Our global comparison of weather-related idioms shows that the Dutch say "it's raining pipe stems," which serves as a fascinating cultural equivalent to the English "raining cats and dogs."
The global comparison of idioms about laziness showed that while English speakers are "couch potatoes," Germans refer to a lazy person as a "lazy skin" or a couch-sitter.
Our final review of international textbooks highlighted the importance of teaching idioms in context, allowing students to make a global comparison of how different societies express common human emotions.
By conducting a global comparison of idioms about luck, our final review revealed that while some cultures associate luck with horseshoes, others view clover or specific numbers as fortunate symbols.
Our global comparison of dining taboos highlights specific rules regarding utensils. A final review of Asian table manners reminds travelers never to stick chopsticks vertically into a bowl of rice.
